Drop dbt-core-experimental-parser from the hard dependency list.

It's declared as an unconditional dependency upstream, but dbt-core never
imports it as a Python module -- it's only shelled out to (dbt/parser/fusion.py)
as an external CLI binary, and only when the user explicitly opts in with
--use-v2-parser / DBT_ENGINE_USE_V2_PARSER (default off). It's also not yet
packaged for conda-forge (see conda-forge/staged-recipes#34267), so this
recipe carries it as a run_constraints entry instead of a hard run dependency
-- see the comment there for the full rationale.

Without this patch, `pip check` fails during the conda-forge build/test step:
the installed dbt-core METADATA still declares dbt-core-experimental-parser
as a hard Requires-Dist (from this same pyproject.toml), even though the
conda recipe deliberately doesn't install it. Dropping it here keeps the
package's own declared metadata consistent with what conda-forge actually
ships, so pip check accurately reflects reality instead of flagging an
absence we intended.

--- a/pyproject.toml
+++ b/pyproject.toml
@@ -58,7 +58,6 @@
     "dbt-common>=1.37.5,<2.0",
     "dbt-adapters>=1.24.5,<2.0",
     "dbt-protos>=1.0.514,<2.0",
-    "dbt-core-experimental-parser>=2.0.0a4,<3",
     "pydantic<3",
     # ----
     # Expect compatibility with all new versions of these packages, so lower bounds only.
